<HEADLINE>
<P>
CUTBACKS IN PROBATION PROGRAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Politicians and government officials do not want to appear soft on crime. 
Behind the scenes, however, they occasionally make decisions that run counter 
to their public posturing on law and order and the war on drugs. A case in 
point is at hand. 
</P>
<P>
Hidden in this year's deliberations over a budget for Los Angeles County lies a 
recommendation from Chief Administrative Officer Richard Dixon that, if 
adopted, will have major impact on the criminal justice system. He is 
recommending the elimination of active supervision for 80,000 adult offenders 
currently on probation. They would be placed on a computerized caseload and 
would not receive any ongoing contact from a probation officer. For all 
practical purposes, probation supervision for 80,000 adults convicted of a wide 
range of offenses, many of which are felonies, will be eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
This is not a plea for the increased use of probation. Rather, if probation is 
ordered let it mean something. Offenders should receive the monitoring and 
enforcement of court orders that judges and the public expect. 
</P>
<P>
Probation is a viable sentencing alternative for certain offenders and when 
combined with the threat of incarceration and enforceable court orders can 
effectively inhibit further law violations. But not in Los Angeles County if 
Dixon's recommendation is accepted. 
</P>
<P>
Make no mistake, the word will spread quickly. After all the effort, expense 
and danger of arrest, trial and conviction, not much is really going to happen 
to the majority of offenders. 
</P>
<P>
Because of severe overcrowding, time spent in jail or prison has been shortened 
tremendously to accommodate a growing backlog of criminals waiting to serve 
their sentences. The revolving door spins at frightening speed. With the 
elimination of probation, there will be no real consequences for those people 
who do not serve even these limited sentences. 
</P>
<P>
These are critical issues that receive little or no attention from the general 
public. What you hear is often far different from what you get when it comes to 
the so-called justice system. In the next few weeks that difference could 
become even greater. 
</P>
<P>
CHARLES HAMSON, Chairman 
</P>
<P>
Supervising Deputy Probation 
</P>
<P>
Officers Assn. 
</P>
<P>
Joint Council, Local 660, SEIU 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
