<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: FRUSTACIS SETTLE SUIT AGAINST INFERTILITY 
CLINIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Against the wishes of the doctor accused of malpractice, Patti Frustaci, a 
Riverside woman who gave birth to the nation's first septuplets in 1985, and 
her husband, Sam, have agreed to settle their suit against the infertility 
clinic that treated her, representatives for both sides said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
Terms of the settlement will not be revealed until it is made final and 
recorded in Santa Monica Superior Court today. 
</P>
<P>
The Frustacis allege infertility specialist Dr. Jaroslav Marik did not properly 
monitor a powerful fertility drug, leading to physical and developmental 
impairment of the septuplets. Only three survive. 
</P>
<P>
Marik denies the allegations and has strenuously objected to any settlement 
discussions, which went on without his consent, a highly unusual occurrence in 
malpractice cases. Browne Greene, the Frustacis' attorney, said Marik will be 
dismissed as a defendant, the only way Tyler Medical Clinic could settle the 
case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
