<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: SCIENCE/TECHNOLOGY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Dean Takahashi, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hughes Accuser: Michael C. Denlinger, the former Hughes Aircraft Co. staff 
engineer who filed a $9.6-billion "whistle-blower" lawsuit against his former 
employer, is back in court. 
</P>
<P>
Denlinger's original suit, filed in June, 1989, charged that Hughes covered up 
flaws in 4.75 million microchips produced in its defense systems since 1985. 
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department, after conducting its own investigation, decided in 
March that it would not join the suit. 
</P>
<P>
The suit was dismissed April 9 for lack of evidence. At the time, Denlinger's 
attorney, William Humphreys of Santa Ana, said the dismissal was a procedural 
matter, and he vowed that he would file an amended suit. 
</P>
<P>
An amended suit, with what Humphreys said are basically the same charges, was 
filed June 6. Richard Dore, a Hughes spokesman, said the company filed its 
answer denying all charges on June 28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
